                            <comment id="16431603" author="paulk" created="Tue, 10 Apr 2018 02:04:41 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The alternative syntax for &lt;tt&gt;b&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;0&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;amp;= false&lt;/tt&gt; is &lt;tt&gt;b&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;0&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; = b&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;0&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;amp; false&lt;/tt&gt; but agreed the binary compound-assignment operators should work and currently don&apos;t. Strangely, Groovy seems to have some support for &quot;&amp;amp;&amp;amp;=&quot; plumbed into the codebase but not at the grammar level. That&apos;s a separate issue.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16433337" author="paulk" created="Wed, 11 Apr 2018 03:09:50 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;One workaround is to use &lt;tt&gt;@CompileStatic&lt;/tt&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
